SIMPLE: evolute
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Evolute
<hw>Ev"o*lute</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>evolutus</ets> unrolled, p. p. of <ets>evolvere</ets>. See
<er>Evolve</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>A curve from which
another curve, called the <inv>involute</inv> or <xex>evolvent</xex>, is
described by the end of a thread gradually wound upon the former, or
unwound from it. See <er>Involute</er>. It is the locus of the centers
of all the circles which are osculatory to the given curve or
evolvent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Any curve may be an <xex>evolute</xex>, the term being
applied to it only in its relation to the involute.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Evolutility</ent>⟦br⟧
